full_reasoning:
Step-by-step reasoning:
• The key psychological mechanism is that participants compare the actual monetary share (split_self) they are offered to a fairness reference given by their token earnings relative to the total (token_self/(token_self+token_opp)) multiplied by the combined earnings. Deviations from this fairness benchmark drive their utility.
• Rather than imposing a linear penalty or quadratic cost for inequity (as in many previous models), we propose that the perceived deviation is transformed nonlinearly. The arctan function is appealing here because it is monotonic, saturates for larger deviations, and preserves the sign of the difference. This captures the intuition that extreme unfairness does not lead to an unbounded penalty.
• In our model, the fairness reference f is computed as the relative token proportion times combined earnings. The normalized deviation δ = (split_self – f)/f measures how far the offer deviates from fairness in relative terms.
• Two learnable parameters are introduced. The first, lambda_param, scales the overall bonus (or penalty) given by the arctan transformation. The second, tau_param, modulates the sensitivity to the normalized deviation by scaling its argument before applying arctan.
• The observable behavior (whether the participant accepts an offer) is then assumed to be guided by the utility U_accept computed from the offered share plus this fairness adjustment. Since we do not model the utility for rejecting an offer here and do not include a noise parameter (handled later by a temperature parameter), the utility alone is sufficient.

The formal model specification and variable descriptions are provided below.

<MODEL>
f = (token_self / (token_self + token_opp)) * combined_earning
δ = (split_self - f) / f
U_accept = split_self + lambda_param * arctan( tau_param * δ )
</MODEL>

